    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>U.N. Embargo's Costs</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Daniel Barkley letter warns that UN embargo will only worsen situation in Ethiopia and Eritrea (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The United Nations arms embargo on Ethiopia and Eritrea (news article, May 19) will only make matters worse. It may reduce the number of arms but raise the cost of procurement; items in short supply, like food, will command higher prices. This is not a sensible policy in light of the fact that both countries, among the poorest in the world, have already spent more than $1 billion on arms since 1998.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The United Nations arms embargo on Ethiopia and Eritrea (news article, May 19) will only make matters worse. It may reduce the number of arms but raise the cost of procurement; items in short supply, like food, will command higher prices. This is not a sensible policy in light of the fact that both countries, among the poorest in the world, have already spent more than $1 billion on arms since 1998.</p>
        <p>The embargo will also encourage both countries to seek other sources for weapons, like Iran, North Korea and Libya. The strategic and diplomatic implications behind the sales might forestall a political settlement. Moreover, certain countries might show less restraint in the weapons they are willing to sell in order to gain foreign exchange revenues.</p>
        <p>The arms embargo will also encourage both combatants to produce arms domestically rather than take risks with foreign suppliers. This would divert scarce human and capital resources away from plowshares toward swords.</p>
        <p>DANIEL BARKLEY  Irvine, Calif., May 19, 2000</p>
      </block>
